Preheat the #oven{} to 220°C/200°C fan/gas mark 7.

Chop the @potatoes{600%g} into 2cm chunks (peeling optional). Place them in a #pot{}.

Cover with @water{to taste}, season with @salt{to taste}, bring to the boil and cook until fork tender, ~{12-18%minutes}.

Once cooked, drain in a #colander{} (reserving a little cooking water) and return to the pot, off the heat.

Add a knob of @butter{to taste} and a splash of @?milk{to taste} or cooking water. Mash using a #potato masher{} until smooth. Season with salt and @pepper{to taste}. Cover to keep warm.

Peel and grate the @garlic{1}(peeled and grated).

Lay the @Irish Chicken Breast{320%g} onto a lined #baking tray{}.

Drizzle with @oil{to taste}, rub over the garlic and season with salt and pepper.

Roast on the top shelf until cooked through, ~{25-30%minutes}.

> IMPORTANT: Wash hands and equipment after handling raw chicken and its packaging. Chicken is cooked when no longer pink in the middle.
> TIP: Notice a stronger smell from your chicken? Don't worry, this is normal due to packaging used to keep it fresh.

Trim the root and the dark green leafy part from the @Leek{1}(trimmed). Halve lengthways then thinly slice.

Trim the @Carrot{2}(trimmed), then halve lengthways (no need to peel). Chop into 1cm wide, 5cm long batons.

Meanwhile, place a large pan over high heat with a drizzle of @oil{to taste}.

Once hot, fry the carrot until starting to char, ~{2-3%minutes}.

Lower heat to medium and cook for ~{1%minute}.

Add a splash of @?water{to taste} and cover with a lid or some #foil{}. Cook until tender, ~{4-5%minutes}.

Remove from the pan, set aside and cover to keep warm.

Return the empty pan to medium-high heat with another drizzle of @?oil{to taste} if needed.

Add the leek then season with salt and pepper. Cook until softened, ~{4-5%minutes}.

Add @Creme Fraiche{110%g}, @Chicken Stock{1%sachet} and @Mustard{1%sachet}, stir well to combine.

Bring to the boil and simmer for ~{4-5%minutes}. Taste and season with salt and pepper, if required.

> TIP: Loosen the sauce with a splash of water if you feel it's too thick.

Thinly slice the chicken and divide between plates.

Serve mash and pan-fried veg alongside.

To finish, spoon over the creamy mustard sauce.